[{"name":"assertion","pos":"noun","content":"<div class=\"entry\" sum=\"619\" hclass=\"entry\" htag=\"section\" id=\"assertion\" hlength=\"9\" sk=\"assertion: :0\" idm_id=\"000003057\"><div class=\"top-container\"><div class=\"top-g\" id=\"assertion_topg_1\"><div class=\"webtop\"><h1 class=\"headword\" hclass=\"headword\" opal_written=\"y\" htag=\"h1\" ox5000=\"y\" id=\"assertion_h_1\">assertion</h1> <span class=\"pos\" htag=\"span\" hclass=\"pos\">noun</span><div class=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"symbols\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/opal?dataset=english&amp;list=opal_written&amp;level=sublist_12\"><span class=\"opal_symbol\" href=\"OPAL_Written::Sublist_12\">OPAL W</span></a></div><span class=\"phonetics\"> <div class=\"phons_br\" hclass=\"phons_br\" wd=\"assertion\" geo=\"br\" htag=\"div\"><div class=\"sound audio_play_button pron-uk icon-audio\" data-src-mp3=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/uk_pron/a/ass/asser/assertion__gb_1.mp3\" data-src-ogg=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/uk_pron_ogg/a/ass/asser/assertion__gb_1.ogg\" title=\"assertion pronunciation\n                    English\" style=\"cursor: pointer\" valign=\"top\">&nbsp;</div><span class=\"phon\">/əˈsɜːʃn/</span></div> <div class=\"phons_n_am\" hclass=\"phons_n_am\" wd=\"assertion\" geo=\"n_am\" htag=\"div\"><div class=\"sound audio_play_button pron-us icon-audio\" data-src-mp3=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/us_pron/a/ass/asser/assertion__us_1.mp3\" data-src-ogg=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/media/english/us_pron_ogg/a/ass/asser/assertion__us_1.ogg\" title=\"assertion pronunciation\n                    American\" style=\"cursor: pointer\" valign=\"top\">&nbsp;</div><span class=\"phon\">/əˈsɜːrʃn/</span></div></span></div><a class=\"responsive_display_inline_on_smartphone link-right\" href=\"#relatedentries\">\n                            jump to other results\n                        </a></div></div><ol class=\"senses_multiple\" htag=\"ol\"><li class=\"sense\" id=\"assertion_sng_1\" cefr=\"c1\" ox5000=\"y\" htag=\"li\" sensenum=\"1\" hclass=\"sense\"><span class=\"sensetop\" hclass=\"sensetop\" htag=\"span\"><div class=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"symbols\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div></span><span class=\"grammar\" hclass=\"grammar\" htag=\"span\">[countable]</span> <span class=\"def\" hclass=\"def\" htag=\"span\">a statement saying that you strongly believe something to be true</span> <span class=\"xrefs\" htag=\"span\" xt=\"nsyn\" hclass=\"xrefs\"><span class=\"prefix\">synonym</span> <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/claim_2\" title=\"claim definition\"><span class=\"xr-g\" bord=\"n\" href=\"claim_subentryg_2:claim_topg_4\"><span class=\"xh\">claim</span></span></a></span><ul class=\"examples\" hclass=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">He was correct in his assertion that the minister had been lying.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">Do you have any evidence to support your assertions?</span></li></ul><div class=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"collapse\"><span class=\"unbox\" unbox=\"synonyms\" id=\"assertion_unbox_1\"><span class=\"box_title\">Synonyms <span class=\"closed\">claim</span></span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unbox\">claim</span><ul class=\"inline\"><li class=\"li\">allegation</li><li class=\"li\">assertion</li></ul><span class=\"p\">These are all words for a statement that something is true, although it has not been proved.</span><ul class=\"deflist\"><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">claim</span> <span class=\"dd\">a statement that something is true, although it has not been proved.</span></li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">allegation</span> <span class=\"dd\">(<span class=\"ei\">rather formal</span>) a public statement that is made without giving proof, accusing somebody of doing something that is wrong or illegal.</span></li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"dt\">assertion</span> <span class=\"dd\">(<span class=\"ei\">rather formal</span>) a statement of something that you strongly believe to be true, although it has not been proved.</span></li></ul> <span class=\"un\"><span class=\"h4\">claim or assertion?</span><span class=\"p\">When the point in doubt is a matter of opinion, not fact, use <span class=\"eb\">assertion</span>: <span class=\"wx\">She made sweeping claims about the role of women in society.</span> When you are talking about a matter of fact, you can use either word; an <span class=\"eb\">assertion</span> may be slightly stronger than a <span class=\"eb\">claim</span> and it is a more formal word.</span></span><span class=\"patterns\">Patterns</span><ul class=\"bullet\"><li class=\"li\">a(n) claim/​allegation/​assertion <span class=\"eb\">that…</span></li><li class=\"li\">a(n) claim/​allegation/​assertion <span class=\"eb\">about/​of</span> something</li><li class=\"li\"><span class=\"eb\">false/​unfounded/​conflicting</span> claims/​allegations/​assertions</li><li class=\"li\">to <span class=\"eb\">make/​deny</span> a(n) claim/​allegation/​assertion</li><li class=\"li\">to <span class=\"eb\">withdraw</span> a(n) claim/​allegation</li></ul></span></span></div><div class=\"collapse\" hclass=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\"><span class=\"unbox\" unbox=\"extra_examples\" id=\"assertion_unbox_2\"><span class=\"box_title\">Extra Examples</span><ul class=\"examples\" hclass=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">Your assertion is not supported by the facts.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">Researchers have recently challenged these assertions.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">The argument needs to progress beyond the simple assertion that criminals are made not born.</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"unx\">They made sweeping assertions about the role of women in society.</span></li></ul></span></div><span class=\"topic-g\"><span class=\"prefix\">Topics </span><a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/opinion-and-argument?level=c1\" title=\"Topic opinion-and-argument\"><span class=\"topic\" href=\"l2:functions:opinion_and_argument?cefr=c1\"><span class=\"topic_name\">Opinion and argument</span><span class=\"topic_cefr\">c1</span></span></a></span><div class=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"collapse\"><span class=\"unbox\" id=\"assertion_unbox_3\" unbox=\"snippet\"><span class=\"box_title\">Oxford Collocations Dictionary</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"unbox\">adjective</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">bold</li><li class=\"li\">confident</li><li class=\"li\">strong</li><li class=\"li\">…</li></ul><span class=\"unbox\">verb + assertion</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">make</li><li class=\"li\">justify</li><li class=\"li\">prove</li><li class=\"li\">…</li></ul><span class=\"unbox\">preposition</span><ul class=\"collocs_list\"><li class=\"li\">assertion about</li></ul><span class=\"xref_to_full_entry\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/collocations/assertion\" title=\" definition in Collocations\n \">full entry</a></span></span></span></div>          \n</li><li class=\"sense\" hclass=\"sense\" sensenum=\"2\" htag=\"li\" ox5000=\"y\" cefr=\"c1\" id=\"assertion_sng_2\"><span class=\"sensetop\" hclass=\"sensetop\" htag=\"span\"><div class=\"symbols\" hclass=\"symbols\" htag=\"div\"><a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/wordlists/oxford3000-5000?dataset=english&amp;list=ox5000&amp;level=c1\"><span class=\"ox5ksym_c1\">&nbsp;</span></a></div></span><span class=\"grammar\" hclass=\"grammar\" htag=\"span\">[uncountable, countable]</span> <span class=\"def\" hclass=\"def\" htag=\"span\">the act of stating, using or claiming something strongly</span><ul class=\"examples\" htag=\"ul\" hclass=\"examples\"><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">the assertion of his authority</span></li><li class=\"\" htag=\"li\"><span class=\"x\">The demonstration was an assertion of the right to peaceful protest.</span></li></ul>      </li><div class=\"collapse\" htag=\"div\" hclass=\"collapse\"><span class=\"unbox\" id=\"assertion_unbox_2\" unbox=\"wordorigin\"><span class=\"box_title\">Word Origin</span><span class=\"body\"><span class=\"p\">late Middle English: from Latin <span class=\"ei\">assertio(n-)</span>, from the verb <span class=\"ei\">asserere</span> ‘claim, affirm’, from <span class=\"ei\">ad-</span> ‘to’ + <span class=\"ei\">serere</span> ‘to join’.</span></span></span></div></ol><span class=\"dictlink-g\"><span class=\"dictlink\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/american_english/assertion\" title=\" definition in American English\n \"><span class=\"xh\">assertion</span></a> in the Oxford Advanced American Dictionary</span><span class=\"dictlink\">See <a class=\"Ref\" href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/academic/assertion\" title=\" definition in Academic English\n \"><span class=\"xh\">assertion</span></a> in the Oxford Learner's Dictionary of Academic English</span></span><div class=\"pron-link\">Check pronunciation:\n                        <a href=\"https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/pronunciation/english/assertion\">assertion</a></div></div>\n","matches":["self-assertion noun"],"relatives":["self-assertion noun"],"nearBys":["assent verb","assert verb","assertion noun","assertive adjective","assertively adverb"]},[{"name":"self-assertion","pos":"